data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_07010c6c811f07f40069f264cd4fc48190aeb41c8ad75c37a1","logprobs":[],"output_index":0,"sequence_number":379,"text":"Token log probabilities are a way of expressing the likelihood of a specific token (often a word or sub-word unit) appearing in a sequence, typically within the context of natural language processing (NLP) models like language models. Here are some key points about them:\n\n1. **Definition**: The log probability of a token is the logarithm of the probability of that token given the preceding context in the text. This is used to stabilize computations, as probabilities can become very small and difficult to handle in arithmetic operations.\n\n2. **Usage**: In NLP, models generate text by predicting the probability of the next token based on the previous tokens. Log probabilities help in selecting the most likely next token or in calculating the overall likelihood of a generated sequence.\n\n3. **Mathematical Expression**: If \\( P(w|context) \\) represents the probability of the token \\( w \\) given a context, the log probability is computed as:\n   \\[\n   \\text{log\\_prob}(w) = \\log(P(w|context))\n   \\]\n   This can be done using natural logarithms or logarithms with base 10.\n\n4. **Interpretation**: A higher log probability (closer to zero in the negative scale) indicates that the token is more likely to occur in the given context, while a more negative value indicates lower likelihood.\n\n5. **Normalizing Outputs**: Log probabilities are often used in conjunction with softmax functions when generating predictions, as they help in normalizing the outputs over all possible tokens.\n\n6. **Applications**: Understanding token log probabilities is essential for tasks such as text generation, language translation, and other applications where predicting sequences of text is crucial.\n\nIn summary, token log probabilities are a fundamental part of how language models evaluate and generate language, allowing them to handle complex sequences in a manageable way."}

